{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Slot A: Behavior says the payload sent to the external API must contain the full taxonomy list.\nSlot B: Failure boundary is module-to-client handoff (request builder + API adapter wiring).\nSlot C: A Unit test of only the builder can pass while adapter mapping drops labels before send.\nFinal label: Integration, based on Slot B boundary wiring and Slot C lower-level miss risk.\nRejection gate: Reject System because behavior text only requires request content correctness, not real network/OS effects; reject Agentic because no dependence on model judgment/output quality.","test_description":"Wire classifier module to a stub transport/client that captures outbound request body; invoke classify with a taxonomy of 4 labels and assert captured payload includes exactly that complete list (no omissions, no substitutions) at dispatch time.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"This test needs cross-module wiring (module -> client payload), which is above Unit and below System.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.72,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Slot A: Behavior is deterministic mapping: out-of-taxonomy provider label -> \"unknown\".\nSlot B: Boundary is local normalization/validation logic in the classifier object.\nSlot C: Integration would be redundant because the failure is in local label-check logic, not OS/network/module handoff.\nFinal label: Unit, because Slot B is a local object boundary and Slot C shows higher level is unnecessary.\nRejection gate: Reject Integration because behavior text focuses on returned value transf